The FDA has approved a game changing medication to help with weight loss and it’s called a semaglutide.

It is not a new medication or class of medication. It is a GLP 1 agonist and in a trial of over 2000 obese patients who are followed over 68 weeks, it was found that the population who got the medication lost significant weight along with participating in a diet and exercise regimen program! 

The efficacy of this medication is great, and it works because it’s used to treat diabetes by mimicking a natural hormone GLP1 that promotes the body to produce more insulin after eating. 

When this happens it reduces blood sugar levels and when that happens weight loss becomes a side effect. The medication starts suppressing your appetite.

Second part of GLP 1 agonist! 💪🏽

👉GLP one agonist are a great choice when you are trying to improve blood sugars, trying to lose weight and if you are high-risk and have multiple medical problems like heart disease and more. 

👉GLP one agonist work because they enhance insulin Secretion and reduce glucagon release which are great for minimizing extreme low blood sugars. They also decrease appetite and signal of the brain that you are full early, regulating your leptin levels. 

Common side effects are nausea, vomiting and diarrhea in the weekly medication. 

For some people GLP one agonists can be linked to acute pancreatitis and should be avoided in people with pancreatic cancer, thyroid cancer and more.

It’s important to know how Leptin and Ghrelin impact your metabolism, your waistline and your weight! 👩🏾‍⚕️🩺🥼 

Both work together as well as independently and indirectly. The correlation is clear as ghrelin increases your hunger and your appetite while leptin decreases your appetite when you are full. 👍🏼 

It’s important to understand how food and nutrition impacts your metabolism. Then only then are you able to improve your metabolism to your favor. 

A medication like a GLP one agonist helps stabilize both leptin and ghrelin by decreasing your appetite and keeping you full longer so your hunger cues change in the right direction and make it easier for you to lose weight and keep it off.

💥Supporting digestion: Drinking water can help support digestion by aiding in the breakdown of food and facilitating the movement of food through the digestive system. It can also help prevent constipation by softening stools and making them easier to pass.

💥Regulating body temperature: When the body gets too hot, it sweats to cool down. Sweat is made up of water and electrolytes, so it is essential to drink water to replace the fluids lost through sweating and maintain proper body temperature.

💥Boosting energy levels: Dehydration can cause fatigue and low energy levels. Drinking enough water can help to prevent dehydration and maintain energy levels throughout the day.

💥Promoting healthy skin: Drinking enough water helps to keep the skin hydrated, which can promote healthy, glowing skin. It can also help to flush out toxins and prevent skin conditions like acne.

Overall, drinking enough water is essential for maintaining optimal body function, and it is important to make sure you are getting enough water each day to support your health and wellbeing.

Ok so let's talk about leptin.

💥Leptin is a hormone that plays a critical role in regulating appetite, metabolism, and energy balance in the body. It is primarily produced by adipose tissue (fat cells) and acts on the brain to signal when the body has had enough food and should stop eating. 

💥Maintaining normal leptin levels is important for overall health, as imbalances in leptin levels have been associated with a range of health issues, including obesity, insulin resistance, and metabolic syndrome. 

💥Checking leptin levels can help identify potential health issues related to leptin imbalances. For example, low leptin levels can indicate a potential issue with the body's ability to produce or respond to the hormone, which can lead to increased appetite, weight gain, and metabolic dysfunction. On the other hand, high leptin levels can indicate leptin resistance, which is when the body no longer responds to leptin signals, leading to increased appetite, weight gain, and other health issues. 

💥Additionally, monitoring leptin levels may be helpful in the management of obesity and related conditions. Leptin supplements or medications that target leptin signaling may be prescribed to help regulate appetite and promote weight loss in individuals with leptin imbalances. 

In summary, checking leptin levels is an important aspect of maintaining overall health and identifying potential issues related to appetite, metabolism, and energy balance.

Allergies occur when your immune system overreacts to a harmless substance, such as pollen, dust mites, pet dander, or certain foods. While there is no cure for allergies, there are several strategies you can use to reduce allergy symptoms:

✅️Avoid allergens: Identify the allergens that trigger your symptoms and try to avoid them. For example, if you are allergic to pollen, try to stay indoors during peak pollen season and keep windows closed. If you are allergic to dust mites, use special covers for your bedding and vacuum frequently.

✅️Use medication: Over-the-counter antihistamines, decongestants, and nasal corticosteroids can help relieve allergy symptoms. If your allergies are severe, your doctor may prescribe stronger medications.

✅️Manage stress: Stress can worsen allergy symptoms, so try to find ways to manage stress, such as exercise, yoga, or meditation.

By listening to binaural beats in a specific frequency range, you can stimulate the desired brainwave activity.

It's important to note that binaural beats may not work for everyone, and they should never be used as a substitute for medical or mental health treatment.

By slowing down your breathing and focusing on the present moment, you can lower your blood pressure, reduce the stress hormone cortisol, and improve your mood. 💥The 4-7-8 breath can be done anywhere, at any time, and is a great tool for managing stress and anxiety in the moment.

🧠🍽️ Insulin regulates blood sugar levels and curbs appetite, while leptin manages energy balance and signals fullness.

👥🤝 Together, they team up to regulate our cravings and keep us satisfied, with insulin suppressing hunger and leptin informing the brain about our energy reserves.

🔄⛔ When insulin resistance arises, it can disrupt the leptin pathway, resulting in leptin resistance. This disturbance can trigger increased appetite, reduced energy expenditure, and weight regulation challenges.

⚖️⚡️ Balancing energy intake and expenditure relies on the intricate dance between insulin and leptin. Insulin facilitates glucose uptake, while leptin communicates energy levels to the brain. Imbalances may lead to weight gain, obesity, and metabolic issues.

↩️📢 Insulin and leptin engage in a feedback loop, where insulin levels impact leptin production. Elevated insulin levels, often linked to insulin resistance and obesity, can boost leptin production. However, resistance to both hormones can disrupt the loop, making appetite regulation and energy balance more challenging.

Unveiling the complex connection between trauma and obesity:

💥Emotional or physical trauma can have a profound impact on weight management. From emotional eating to disrupted stress response, altered appetite regulation to unhealthy coping mechanisms, trauma affects us in multifaceted ways.

When emotions overflow, food often becomes a refuge, leading to weight struggles. The stress response and cortisol overload caused by trauma can disrupt weight management, potentially resulting in abdominal fat accumulation.

Trauma messes with appetite regulation, making it difficult to recognize genuine needs and leading to overeating and weight gain. Depression, anxiety, and PTSD, which often accompany trauma, alter our relationship with food, further hindering weight management efforts.

Unhealthy coping mechanisms such as substance abuse, isolation, and sedentary behavior can become familiar faces after trauma, contributing to weight gain. Sleep disturbances, like insomnia and disrupted sleep patterns, are also common companions of trauma, affecting hormones, increasing appetite, and impairing metabolism.

🌟 Leptin vs. Leptin Resistance 🌟

Leptin Function: 💭🍽️ Leptin, produced by fat cells, regulates appetite and energy balance. It signals the brain when fat stores are sufficient, reducing appetite and boosting energy expenditure.

Leptin Resistance: ❌🤔 Leptin resistance occurs when cells become less sensitive to leptin's signals, leading to persistent hunger and reduced energy expenditure, contributing to obesity.

Appetite Regulation: 🍔🏋️‍♂️ Leptin promotes satiety and balance in normal function, while resistance results in uncontrollable hunger, even with high fat levels.

Energy Expenditure: 🏃‍♀️🔥 Leptin normally increases activity and fat utilization, but resistance reduces metabolism and fat burning.

Impact on Obesity: ⚖️🚫 Balanced leptin helps maintain healthy weight, while resistance disrupts appetite control, increasing obesity risk.

Contributing Factors: 🧬🍔 Genetics, diet, stress, sleep, and inflammation affect leptin resistance, while a healthy lifestyle supports normal leptin function.

Potential Interventions: 🏋️‍♀️🥦 A healthy diet, exercise, and sleep support normal leptin, while addressing resistance may require lifestyle changes and medical assistance.

Understanding the differences between normal leptin function and leptin resistance is crucial for tackling obesity and metabolic disorders. Research on leptin resistance offers insights for managing weight and promoting overall health. 📚🤝

Cracking the Code on Obesity: How Sneaky Obesogens Play with Your Hunger Hormones 🍔🔍

Ever heard of obesogens? They're like undercover agents that mess with your body's weight game. 

📸Picture this: you've got a hormone called leptin that's supposed to tell your brain when you're full and keep your weight in check. But obesogens throw a wrench in the works, and here's how they do it:

👉Quiet Cravings: Obesogens can mess with how your body makes leptin, so your brain doesn't get the memo that you're full. It's like your hunger switch is stuck on 'on,' making you feel hungry all the time.

👉Confused Signals: Imagine leptin as a messenger trying to tell your brain about your energy stores. Obesogens mess with this message, confusing your brain's control center. So, you end up not knowing if you're really hungry or not.

👉Stubborn Resistance: If obesogens stick around for a while, they can make your body ignore leptin's signals. It's like your brain starts wearing noise-canceling headphones when leptin tries to talk. This messes up your body's balance between eating and burning calories.

Think of obesogens as the troublemakers in your weight management story. By understanding how they team up with leptin, we're getting closer to solving the mystery of why it's sometimes tough to keep those extra pounds at bay. 🕵️‍♀️🌍🍕

Understanding Leptin: Your Body's Hunger Messenger 📢🧠 

Leptin, a crucial hormone produced by your fat cells, plays a pivotal role in maintaining your appetite. It's like your body's internal communication system, telling your brain when you're hungry, when you're full, and when you might need to eat more. 🍔🍏 

However, sometimes this hormone can go haywire, especially after years of crash diets, inflammation, stress, or certain medications. The result? Leptin resistance, which can make it harder to manage your weight and hunger cues. 🤯🍽️ 

But here's the exciting part: For those who qualify, there are prescription solutions that can help tackle leptin resistance head-on. These prescription options, known as incretins or GLP-1 agonists, have the potential to restore balance to your leptin levels, making it easier to regulate your appetite and maintain a healthy weight. 💊🏋️‍♀️ 

So, the next time you find yourself struggling with weight management or hunger control, remember that there's hope and help available. Leptin resistance can be conquered, and sometimes, the key to success lies in the right prescription. Stay informed, stay healthy! 💪

Allergies occur when your immune system overreacts to harmless substances like pollen, dust mites, pet dander, or certain foods. While there's no cure, here are strategies to alleviate symptoms:

✅️ Avoid Allergens: Identify triggers and minimize exposure. Stay indoors during peak pollen season, use allergen-proof bedding covers, and keep windows closed.

✅️ Medication Options: Over-the-counter remedies like antihistamines and decongestants can provide relief. Ask your doctor about stronger prescriptions if needed.

Tired of drowsy antihistamines? Try my favorites, D-hist & D-hist Jr. They're packed with natural ingredients like bromelain, quercetin, vitamin C, stinging nettles & Nac to soothe itchy eyes, ears, throat, and congestion!

✅️ Immunotherapy: Consider allergy shots or sublingual immunotherapy to reduce allergen sensitivity over time.

✅️ Clean Living: Use HEPA filters in your vacuum and air purifier to trap allergens, and maintain good hygiene.

✅️ Stress Management: Stress can exacerbate allergies, so prioritize relaxation techniques like exercise, yoga, or meditation.

✅️ Hydration: Stay hydrated to keep nasal passages moist and reduce symptoms.

Remember, allergies vary, so consult your doctor, allergist, or me for personalized advice if managing them is a challenge. Together, we can tackle allergies and improve your quality of life! 🌿💪

🎄✨Holiday Health Tips for a Season of Well-Being! 🌟

🍽️ Balance Indulgence with Nutrient-Rich Choices:
Enjoy festive treats in moderation and balance them with nutrient-packed foods to support your overall health.

💧Stay Hydrated:
With the hustle and bustle, it's easy to forget to drink water. Keep yourself hydrated to maintain energy levels and support digestion.

😴Prioritize Quality Sleep:
Ensure you get enough rest during the holidays. Quality sleep is crucial for overall well-being and helps manage stress.

🏋️Stay Active:
Incorporate physical activity into your holiday routine, whether it's a winter walk, a dance party, or a quick home workout. Exercise boosts mood and energy.

🍽️ Mindful Eating:
Pay attention to your body's hunger and fullness cues. Be present during meals, savoring each bite, and avoiding mindless overeating.

🧘Manage Stress:
The holidays can be stressful. Practice stress-reducing techniques such as deep breathing, meditation, or a calming hobby to maintain emotional well-being.

🍷Limit Alcohol Intake:
While celebrating is part of the holiday spirit, it's essential to drink alcohol in moderation to support your health and well-being.

🍲 Practice Food Safety:
Ensure food safety during holiday gatherings. Properly store and handle food to prevent foodborne illnesses.

🤝 Connect with Loved Ones:
Nurture your emotional health by spending quality time with family and friends. Social connections contribute to a sense of well-being.

🎯 Set Realistic Expectations:
Manage expectations during the holiday season. Be realistic about what you can accomplish, and don't hesitate to ask for help if needed.

Remember, the holidays are a time to enjoy, reflect, and appreciate. 

Taking care of your health allows you to fully savor the magic of the season! 🌟
